  "response": "There are many legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. BCCI Holdings (1991)\n- Landmark case involving extensive international money laundering\n- Resulted in significant banking reforms\n\n2. Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) Scandal\n- Major international money laundering investigation\n- Led to significant regulatory changes\n\n3. United States v. Martin Act Cases\n- Established broad prosecutorial powers for financial crimes\n- Important for securities fraud and money laundering investigations\n\n4. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Comprehensive legal framework for money laundering prosecution\n- Expanded definitions and enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International standards for anti-money laundering practices\n- Influenced legal frameworks globally\n\nThese cases have shaped modern anti-money laundering legal approaches, establishing important principles for investigation, prosecution, and prevention. Would you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?",
